DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(84)80003-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199684800033
AB  - This paper develops a model of the black market for foreign exchange in which black market currency is demanded and supplied by firms engaged in smuggling. It is demonstrated that quotas or foreign exchange rationing are not necessary to induce the coexistence of legal and black foreign exchange markets. Variants of the model analyze the implications of capital flight, unbalanced trade, quotas, foreign exchange licensing, and economies with more than two goods.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Trade warfare: Tariffs and cartels
AU  - Brander, James A.
AU  - Spencer, Barbara J.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 16
IS  - 3
SP  - 227
EP  - 242
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(84)80002-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199684800021
AB  - National governments have incentives to intervene in international markets, particularly in encouraging export cartels and in imposing tariffs on imports from imperfectly competitive foreign firms. Although the optimal response to foreign monopoly is usually a tariff, a specific subsidy will be optimal if demand is very convex, as with constant elasticity demand. If ad valorem tariffs or subsidies are considered, a subsidy is optimal if the elasticity of demand increases as consumption increases. The critical conditions in both ad valorem and specific cases hold generally for Cournot oligopoly. Noncooperative international policy equilibrium will be characterized by export cartels and rent-extracting tariffs.
ER  - 

